</code></pre> <pre><code>++j, --i // two expressions count as one for syntax purposes
int i, j; // comma is a separator here, not an operator
</code></pre> forstr2.cpp - Example of comma separator trick <pre><code>// forstr2.cpp -- reversing an array
#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
int main()
{
    using namespace std;
    cout &lt;&lt; "Enter a word: ";
    string word;
    cin &gt;&gt; word;

    // physically modify string object
    char temp;
    int i, j;
    for (j = 0, i = word.size() - 1; j &lt; i; --i, ++j)
    { // start block
        temp = word[i];
        word[i] = word[j];
        word[j] = temp;
    } // end block
    cout &lt;&lt; word &lt;&lt; "\nDone\n";
    return 0;
}
</code></pre> <p>The relational operators have a lower precedence than the arithmetic operators.That means this expression: <code>x + 3 &gt; y - 2 // Expression 1</code> corresponds to this: <code>(x + 3) &gt; (y - 2) // Expression 2</code> and not to the following: <code>x + (3 &gt; y) - 2 // Expression 3</code></p> <pre><code>strcmp(word, "mate") != 0 // strings are not the same
</code></pre> compstr1.cpp - Example comparison c-string in search for word <pre><code>// compstr1.cpp -- comparing strings using arrays
